Doctor Lecter.

256
00:16:36,411 --> 00:16:38,421
I am so embarrassed.

257
00:16:39,094 --> 00:16:41,095
You didn't get my message?

258
00:16:41,097 --> 00:16:43,781
I canceled your appointment
with Will Graham.

259
00:16:43,783 --> 00:16:46,017
Is everything all right?

260
00:16:46,019 --> 00:16:48,636
I can explain.
Shall we?

261
00:16:51,160 --> 00:16:55,031
Will is at a delicate
point in his therapy.

262
00:16:55,151 --> 00:16:58,109
I don't want to confuse him
any more than he already is.

263
00:16:58,345 --> 00:16:59,201
Confuse him?

264
00:16:59,566 --> 00:17:01,903
Isn't it your opinion he's
an intelligent psychopath?

265
00:17:02,023 --> 00:17:05,104
It was, but my opinion is evolving.

266
00:17:05,548 --> 00:17:08,900
After administering a
narcoanalytic interview,

267
00:17:09,285 --> 00:17:12,603
therapeutically vital
information has come to light.

268
00:17:12,605 --> 00:17:16,190
- What sort of information?
- What Will Graham suffers from

269
00:17:16,192 --> 00:17:19,276
may not be a single condition,
but a continuum

270
00:17:19,278 --> 00:17:21,278
of illnesses, all with different

271
00:17:21,280 --> 00:17:23,981
neurological mechanisms.
Some naturally occurring,

272
00:17:23,983 --> 00:17:27,651
- others appear to have been induced.
- Induced?

273
00:17:27,653 --> 00:17:30,153
Induced by whom?

274
00:17:30,155 --> 00:17:33,106
Did you ever use any kind
of light stimulation

275
00:17:33,108 --> 00:17:35,125
in your treatment?

276
00:17:35,127 --> 00:17:38,212
Light stimulation is a
standard tool for neurotherapy.

277
00:17:38,214 --> 00:17:41,481
Evidently, it was overloading
his visual cortex.

278
00:17:41,483 --> 00:17:43,917
Creating seizures, time loss,

279
00:17:43,919 --> 00:17:46,119
gaps in his memory.

280
00:17:46,121 --> 00:17:48,672
Almost strategically, it seems.

281
00:17:51,659 --> 00:17:53,644
You're suggesting
it was intentional?

282
00:17:53,646 --> 00:17:55,646
All our conversations
about psychic driving.

283
00:17:55,648 --> 00:17:58,348
You were so curious and eager
to hear what I had to say

284
00:17:58,350 --> 00:18:01,268
- while saying very little yourself.
- I had very little to say.

285
00:18:01,270 --> 00:18:04,354
I have been thinking
about the possibility

286
00:18:04,356 --> 00:18:07,708
that you may have been psychic
driving Will Graham all along.

287
00:18:10,194 --> 00:18:12,613
A bold accusation, Frederick.

288
00:18:12,615 --> 00:18:15,349
You are not the only psychiatrist
accused of making a patient kill.

289
00:18:17,685 --> 00:18:22,072
We have to stick together.

290
00:18:28,296 --> 00:18:30,847
Last time I did this,

291
00:18:30,849 --> 00:18:33,216
this isn't how I did this.

292
00:18:33,218 --> 00:18:35,469
The young man at the dispensary

293
00:18:35,471 --> 00:18:38,338
calls this "purple kush."

294
00:18:48,299 --> 00:18:50,284
He says

295
00:18:50,286 --> 00:18:52,736
all his cancer patients

296
00:18:52,738 --> 00:18:56,707
love its "deep body stone."
(chuckling)

297
00:18:56,709 --> 00:18:59,993
May I?

298
00:18:59,995 --> 00:19:03,380
- Do you still get drug tested?
- Oh, come on, gimme that thing.

299
00:19:09,554 --> 00:19:12,506
I'm supporting my wife.

300
00:19:18,646 --> 00:19:22,416
I filled out my advadirect.

301
00:19:22,418 --> 00:19:25,402
I added a DNR.

302
00:19:25,404 --> 00:19:28,855
Oh, you are harshing
my buzz right now.

303
00:19:28,857 --> 00:19:32,609
I read an article the other day

304
00:19:32,611 --> 00:19:34,911
about magnetic hyperthermia.

305
00:19:34,913 --> 00:19:38,332
It's looking promising
as a treatment

306
00:19:38,334 --> 00:19:41,168
for lung cancer.

307
00:19:49,093 --> 00:19:51,128
Come here.

308
00:19:53,097 --> 00:19:57,167
I know what to expect
from lung cancer.

309
00:19:57,169 --> 00:20:00,070
I am my mother's daughter,

310
00:20:00,072 --> 00:20:03,306
and I watched her
go through exactly

311
00:20:03,308 --> 00:20:06,309
- what I am going through now.
- I know.

312
00:20:06,311 --> 00:20:09,730
Hey... I remember

313
00:20:09,732 --> 00:20:12,532
sitting by her bed

314
00:20:12,534 --> 00:20:14,651
when she woke up
in so much pain

315
00:20:14,653 --> 00:20:16,903
that all she could do
was scream my name.

316
00:20:19,523 --> 00:20:21,625
I didn't know how to help her.

317
00:20:21,627 --> 00:20:23,660
So I did nothing.

318
00:20:23,662 --> 00:20:25,579
There was nothing you could do.

319
00:20:25,581 --> 00:20:28,148
And there will be a time
when there is nothing

320
00:20:28,150 --> 00:20:30,634
you can do.

321
00:20:30,636 --> 00:20:34,137
And I don't want you
to remember me

322
00:20:34,139 --> 00:20:38,425
pleading with you
to make the pain go away.

323
00:20:38,427 --> 00:20:42,746
Oh, I'm not going
to remember you that way.

324
00:20:42,748 --> 00:20:45,482
First of all,
I'm going to remember you

325
00:20:45,484 --> 00:20:48,485
walking along the quays
of Italy in the sunshine

326
00:20:48,487 --> 00:20:50,954
with a trail of signori
behind you

327
00:20:50,956 --> 00:20:54,357
shouting "bella,
bella, bella."

328
00:20:54,359 --> 00:20:56,927
And I'm going to remember

329
00:20:56,929 --> 00:21:00,063
that your hands...

330
00:21:00,065 --> 00:21:04,017
that they smelled of thyme when
you came in from the garden.

331
00:21:04,019 --> 00:21:06,036
And garlic and onions

332
00:21:06,038 --> 00:21:09,556
every time you left the kitchen.
(laughing)

333
00:21:11,742 --> 00:21:15,479
I'm going to remember you as
beautiful as you are right now.

334
00:21:17,932 --> 00:21:20,383
Well, good.

335
00:21:22,353 --> 00:21:24,738
Good.

336
00:21:38,619 --> 00:21:41,238
Duncan Halloran,
fifty-two, divorced, bankrupt.

337
00:21:41,240 --> 00:21:43,457
Reported missing
six months ago.

338
00:21:43,459 --> 00:21:45,876
And what do we know
about his death?

339
00:21:45,878 --> 00:21:49,129
Considering any post-mortem morphological
changes, this guy's white blood cell count

340
00:21:49,131 --> 00:21:51,281
- was through the roof when he died.
- You're telling me

341
00:21:51,283 --> 00:21:53,834
his killer was a fever
and/or a massive infection?

342
00:21:53,836 --> 00:21:57,003
- Lock 'em both up.
- No family. No money.

343
00:21:57,005 --> 00:21:59,756
No reason to live.
Alive, dead, or dying,

344
00:21:59,758 --> 00:22:01,975
- who put him under the tree?
- It's possible

345
00:22:01,977 --> 00:22:04,978
we're dealing with a highly motivated
religious individual here.

346
00:22:04,980 --> 00:22:08,982
- Explain. - In Hinduism, honey is one of
the five elixirs of immortality.

347
00:22:08,984 --> 00:22:11,985
In Christianity, the bee
is considered to be

348
00:22:11,987 --> 00:22:15,739
an emblem of Christ; his
mildness and mercy on one side,

349
00:22:15,741 --> 00:22:19,309
- his Old Testament justice on the other.
- OK. The orbital bone,

350
00:22:19,311 --> 00:22:22,579
his sphenoid, um, behind where
the eyeballs would usually be,

351
00:22:22,581 --> 00:22:25,198
there's tiny punctures.
Something long and sharp

352
00:22:25,200 --> 00:22:27,751
was pushed in his brain.

353
00:22:27,753 --> 00:22:31,421
Jack, this guy was lobotomized.

354
00:22:35,276 --> 00:22:39,045
- How are you feeling today?
- Not well.

355
00:22:39,047 --> 00:22:42,682
My arthritis is killing me.
I can't take much more of it.

356
00:22:42,684 --> 00:22:46,052
A course of bee venom
therapy would soothe

357
00:22:46,054 --> 00:22:48,221
the inflammation.

358
00:22:48,223 --> 00:22:50,273
I can barely afford
<i>this</i> treatment.

359
00:22:50,275 --> 00:22:53,443
That's a problem
for another day.

360
00:22:53,445 --> 00:22:55,896
Now,

361
00:22:55,898 --> 00:22:59,583
you just quiet your mind.

362
00:22:59,585 --> 00:23:02,519
Just live in the present.

363
00:23:05,022 --> 00:23:07,390
- You feel that?
- No.

364
00:23:07,392 --> 00:23:09,376
Good.

365
00:23:09,378 --> 00:23:11,945
You feel that?

366
00:23:11,947 --> 00:23:14,514
- No.
- Good.

367
00:23:17,835 --> 00:23:19,803
Feel that?

368
00:23:19,805 --> 00:23:22,889
I can't feel anything.

369
00:23:22,891 --> 00:23:25,976
Good.

370
00:23:28,312 --> 00:23:31,431
Then you won't feel this...

371
00:23:41,409 --> 00:23:46,029
(whimpering)

372
00:24:16,770 --> 00:24:20,898
Mister, you're not supposed
to stare at the sun.

373
00:24:21,018 --> 00:24:23,701
It'll hurt your eyes.

374
00:24:35,220 --> 00:24:39,140
Multiple holes in this guy.
Over a dozen.

375
00:24:39,142 --> 00:24:41,425
Both eye sockets.

376
00:24:41,427 --> 00:24:43,594
The-the lesions have severed

377
00:24:43,596 --> 00:24:45,696
most of the nerve tract
in the frontal lobe.

378
00:24:45,698 --> 00:24:48,616
He's covered in bee stings
like he got swarmed.

379
00:24:48,618 --> 00:24:51,869
Must be floating in apitoxin,
or he doesn't feel a thing.

380
00:24:51,871 --> 00:24:54,572
Yeah, the not feeling anything has
got nothing to do with bee stings.

381
00:24:54,574 --> 00:24:56,409
Welcome to the world
of the living dead.

382
00:24:57,010 --> 00:24:58,376
There's a pattern.

383
00:24:58,378 --> 00:25:01,429
- Hey.
- Hey...

384
00:25:01,431 --> 00:25:04,732
- Look what the cat's dragged in.
- What are you looking at?

385
00:25:04,734 --> 00:25:07,318
(both): A pattern.

386
00:25:07,320 --> 00:25:10,755
See, some of the bee stings triggered
an allergic reaction, others didn't.

387
00:25:10,757 --> 00:25:13,024
The inflamed bee stings
were all in line

388
00:25:13,026 --> 00:25:15,743
with the body's meridian,
on acupuncture points.

389
00:25:15,745 --> 00:25:19,363
The bee stings are
hiding the needle marks.

390
00:25:19,365 --> 00:25:20,831
What did you say?

391
00:25:20,833 --> 00:25:24,602
Uh, the bee stings are
hiding the needle marks?

392
00:25:53,482 --> 00:25:56,233
Stitches are hiding stitches.

393
00:25:59,988 --> 00:26:01,956
<i>Only by going deep</i>
<i>beneath the skin</i>

394
00:26:01,958 --> 00:26:06,293
<i>will you understand the nature</i>
<i>of this killer's pathology.</i>

395
00:26:17,389 --> 00:26:20,307
He took his kidney.

396
00:26:20,309 --> 00:26:23,227
I feel like I'm losing my mind.

397
00:26:23,229 --> 00:26:27,648
Tell me if he's real.

398
00:26:27,650 --> 00:26:31,018
- I don't see anyone.
- No, he's right there.

399
00:26:31,020 --> 00:26:33,604
- There's no one there. We're alone.
- You're lying.

400
00:26:33,606 --> 00:26:35,823
You came here alone. Do you
remember coming alone?

401
00:26:35,825 --> 00:26:38,526
- Please don't lie to me.
- Garrett Jacob Hobbs is dead.

402
00:26:38,528 --> 00:26:42,279
- You killed him. You watched him die.
- What's happening to me?

403
00:26:42,281 --> 00:26:45,750
Will. Will, you're having

404
00:26:45,752 --> 00:26:48,169
an episode. I want you
to hand me over the gun.

405
00:26:48,171 --> 00:26:50,788
Will, I want you
to hand me your...

406
00:26:50,790 --> 00:26:53,374
Will...

407
00:27:11,526 --> 00:27:14,812
He's had a mild seizure.

408
00:27:14,814 --> 00:27:18,449
That... doesn't seem
to bother you.

409
00:27:18,451 --> 00:27:21,285
I said it was mild.

410
00:27:30,479 --> 00:27:34,498
Are you the man who claimed
to be the Chesapeake Ripper?

411
00:27:36,218 --> 00:27:38,969
Why do you say "claimed"?

412
00:27:38,971 --> 00:27:41,439
Because you're not.

413
00:27:41,441 --> 00:27:43,891
You know you're not and
you don't know much more

414
00:27:43,893 --> 00:27:46,093
about who you are beyond that.

415
00:27:48,497 --> 00:27:50,514
Are <i>you</i>
<i>the Ripper?</i>

416
00:27:54,086 --> 00:27:56,987
A terrible thing,

417
00:27:56,989 --> 00:27:59,924
to have your identity
taken from you.

418
00:28:23,632 --> 00:28:26,050
Whoever killed James Gray
didn't just take his leg.

419
00:28:26,052 --> 00:28:28,435
Sutures hidden
beneath the stitching

420
00:28:28,437 --> 00:28:30,638
that wove him into the mural. One
crime made to look like another.

421
00:28:30,640 --> 00:28:33,891
Like the Copycat.

422
00:28:33,893 --> 00:28:37,795
And...

423
00:28:37,797 --> 00:28:39,546
the Chesapeake Ripper.

424
00:28:39,881 --> 00:28:42,747
Now you're saying Hannibal
Lecter is the Chesapeake Ripper?

425
00:28:44,120 --> 00:28:46,652
I'm saying also the Chesapeake Ripper.

426
00:28:46,772 --> 00:28:49,423
Um...

427
00:28:49,425 --> 00:28:51,425
were the kidneys
surgically removed?

428
00:28:51,427 --> 00:28:53,840
- Yes.
- Dr. Lecter was a surgeon.

429
00:28:53,960 --> 00:28:57,631
I know he was. I asked him to
consult on James Gray's autopsy.

430
00:28:59,918 --> 00:29:01,919
You what?

431
00:29:01,921 --> 00:29:04,421
If you invited him

432
00:29:04,423 --> 00:29:05,982
with an actual agenda,
Hannibal would know it.

433
00:29:06,102 --> 00:29:08,439
- He pointed me to the evidence.
- He pointed you

434
00:29:08,559 --> 00:29:11,162
to an absence of evidence.

435
00:29:11,164 --> 00:29:13,397
He's baiting a hook, Beverly.

436
00:29:13,399 --> 00:29:16,650
He's toying with you.
Go to Jack. Tell him everything.

437
00:29:16,652 --> 00:29:20,104
I can't bring this to Jack
until I can back it up.

438
00:29:20,106 --> 00:29:23,056
Stay away

439
00:29:23,058 --> 00:29:25,559
from Hannibal Lecter.

440
00:29:27,529 --> 00:29:30,347
The Chesapeake Ripper
kept surgical trophies.

441
00:29:30,349 --> 00:29:34,001
If Hannibal's the ripper, what's
he doing with his trophies?

442
00:29:42,344 --> 00:29:45,462
(crows cawing)

443
00:29:57,943 --> 00:30:00,477
He's eating them.

444
00:30:27,264 --> 00:30:28,604
***

445
00:30:29,659 --> 00:30:30,590
Yes.

446
00:30:30,933 --> 00:30:33,151
I'm Special Agent
Jack Crawford with the FBI.

447
00:30:33,153 --> 00:30:35,153
This is Agent Zeller
and Agent Price.

448
00:30:35,155 --> 00:30:37,684
We'd like to speak with you about
two of your former patients.

449
00:30:37,804 --> 00:30:39,453
Would you like to come in?

450
00:30:40,098 --> 00:30:43,332
When was the last time you saw
Duncan Halloran or Lloyd Roat?

451
00:30:43,334 --> 00:30:46,018
Whenever our last
appointments were.

452
00:30:46,020 --> 00:30:48,936
- I can check in my calendar, if you want.
- Sure.

453
00:30:49,071 --> 00:30:52,432
- Have you found them?
- Yes, we have.

454
00:30:52,816 --> 00:30:54,816
Mr. Halloran is deceased.

455
00:30:54,818 --> 00:30:58,436
And Mr. Roat
might as well be.

456
00:30:58,438 --> 00:31:00,489
Whew...

457
00:31:00,609 --> 00:31:04,685
- Poor Mr. Halloran...
- What were you treating him for?

458
00:31:05,087 --> 00:31:08,822
That man trudged
from disease to disease.

459
00:31:08,824 --> 00:31:12,259
He had severe combined
immunodeficiency.

460
00:31:12,261 --> 00:31:15,545
Life didn't seem
to be going his way.

461
00:31:15,547 --> 00:31:17,580
- Please.
- Thank you.

462
00:31:20,768 --> 00:31:23,453
Hm...

463
00:31:23,455 --> 00:31:26,106
I find that, uh,

464
00:31:26,108 --> 00:31:29,693
people don't get their own way

465
00:31:29,695 --> 00:31:32,128
because, um,

466
00:31:32,130 --> 00:31:34,998
they often don't know themselves

467
00:31:35,000 --> 00:31:38,718
where that way leads.

468
00:31:38,720 --> 00:31:41,504
Mr. Halloran,
he couldn't envision

469
00:31:41,506 --> 00:31:43,874
a dignified end of life.

470
00:31:43,876 --> 00:31:47,294
So, it's much nicer to die,

471
00:31:47,296 --> 00:31:50,897
well, for him,
to die in a meadow,

472
00:31:50,899 --> 00:31:54,434
a head full of bees.

473
00:31:57,471 --> 00:32:00,674
- Have you tried the honey?
- No.

474
00:32:00,676 --> 00:32:03,910
I couldn't bring myself to
either. It seemed

475
00:32:03,912 --> 00:32:06,580
too morbid.

476
00:32:06,582 --> 00:32:08,665
So you left him in the field

477
00:32:08,667 --> 00:32:11,101
- to die?
- I brought him

478
00:32:11,103 --> 00:32:14,854
to the field to die.
I didn't kill him.

479
00:32:14,856 --> 00:32:17,107
I quieted his mind

480
00:32:17,109 --> 00:32:19,092
so that he could die in peace.

481
00:32:19,094 --> 00:32:22,145
And Mr. Roat?

482
00:32:22,147 --> 00:32:25,515
- You quieted his mind, too?
- Oh, him.

483
00:32:25,517 --> 00:32:27,517
He suffered

484
00:32:27,519 --> 00:32:30,553
crippling arthritis.

485
00:32:30,555 --> 00:32:33,390
After he was quieted...

486
00:32:35,359 --> 00:32:39,195
...I saw him walk pain-free
for the very first time

487
00:32:39,197 --> 00:32:41,798
in his life.

488
00:32:41,800 --> 00:32:45,385
I can't make pain go away,

489
00:32:45,387 --> 00:32:48,939
but I can make it so that
it doesn't matter.

490
00:32:50,958 --> 00:32:53,760
I-I protected them.

491
00:32:53,762 --> 00:32:56,313
I protected these people

492
00:32:56,315 --> 00:32:58,748
from hopelessness.

493
00:32:58,750 --> 00:33:02,685
And that's beautiful.

494
00:33:09,627 --> 00:33:11,995
Please come in.

495
00:33:11,997 --> 00:33:13,997
It's a little unnerving,

496
00:33:13,999 --> 00:33:17,367
not being able to walk
across the floor.

497
00:33:17,369 --> 00:33:21,171
Nothing can be so unnerving
for someone strong

498
00:33:21,173 --> 00:33:23,473
as being weak.

499
00:33:25,676 --> 00:33:29,346
I was so weak
after chemotherapy,

500
00:33:29,348 --> 00:33:32,482
Jack had to
physically pick me up.

501
00:33:32,484 --> 00:33:34,934
It was the second time

502
00:33:34,936 --> 00:33:37,153
he carried me
across the threshold.

503
00:33:39,940 --> 00:33:42,325
I brought you something.

504
00:33:42,327 --> 00:33:44,344
A gift?

505
00:33:49,617 --> 00:33:52,686
Paying my debt.

506
00:33:52,688 --> 00:33:55,672
Coq Gaulois.

507
00:33:55,674 --> 00:33:58,425
For helping me understand

508
00:33:58,427 --> 00:34:01,478
that death is not a defeat,

509
00:34:01,480 --> 00:34:04,464
but a cure.

510
00:34:14,658 --> 00:34:16,643
What have you taken, Bella?

511
00:34:16,645 --> 00:34:19,662
My morphine.

512
00:34:19,664 --> 00:34:21,698
Every bit of it.

513
00:34:26,387 --> 00:34:30,056
I didn't want to die at home.

514
00:34:30,058 --> 00:34:32,992
I didn't want Jack to find me.

515
00:34:34,962 --> 00:34:38,064
I didn't want him
to make that call...

516
00:34:40,568 --> 00:34:44,771
...to be in the room
with my body,

517
00:34:44,773 --> 00:34:48,241
waiting...

518
00:34:48,243 --> 00:34:52,345
for it to become
some ceremonial object

519
00:34:52,347 --> 00:34:55,348
apart from him,

520
00:34:55,350 --> 00:34:58,718
separate

521
00:34:58,720 --> 00:35:01,921
from who I was,

522
00:35:01,923 --> 00:35:04,891
someone he can only...

523
00:35:08,429 --> 00:35:10,997
...hold in his mind.

524
00:35:17,805 --> 00:35:21,691
You denied him his goodbye.

525
00:35:21,693 --> 00:35:24,944
I denied him...

526
00:35:24,946 --> 00:35:28,998
a painful goodbye.

527
00:35:32,603 --> 00:35:36,556
And allowed myself
a peaceful one.

528
00:35:40,194 --> 00:35:42,962
Tell Jack...

529
00:35:47,651 --> 00:35:51,488
...I love him very much.

530
00:35:51,490 --> 00:35:53,656
Yes.

531
00:36:00,898 --> 00:36:03,500
Goodbye,

532
00:36:03,502 --> 00:36:06,352
Dr. Lecter.

533
00:36:30,661 --> 00:36:32,679
Goodbye, Bella.

534
00:38:13,640 --> 00:38:15,992
Hey. Have you seen Jack?

535
00:38:15,994 --> 00:38:17,994
Oh. No, no, no,
there was, uh,

536
00:38:17,996 --> 00:38:19,996
some emergency with his wife.
Dr. Lecter called

537
00:38:19,998 --> 00:38:22,716
- from the hospital, asked him to come down.
- Is Mrs. Crawford okay?

538
00:38:22,718 --> 00:38:24,951
I don't know.
He didn't say.

539
00:38:26,904 --> 00:38:30,106
So Hannibal's
at the hospital, too?

540
00:38:40,184 --> 00:38:42,769
(moaning softly)

541
00:38:50,728 --> 00:38:53,846
- Hi, baby.
- Hey.

542
00:38:55,900 --> 00:38:59,302
I'm here.

543
00:38:59,304 --> 00:39:01,604
I'm here.

544
00:39:18,656 --> 00:39:22,058
What are you doing here?

545
00:39:24,095 --> 00:39:26,129
I want to apologize.

546
00:39:28,566 --> 00:39:30,934
I couldn't honor
what you asked of me.

547
00:39:41,912 --> 00:39:44,581
I'm sorry.

548
00:39:52,256 --> 00:39:55,074
(coughing)

549
00:39:59,380 --> 00:40:01,414
Get out.

550
00:40:58,572 --> 00:41:00,607
Gotcha.

551
00:41:13,170 --> 00:41:15,572
(creaking)

552
